s in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]]. Gabriel Wortman killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people and set fire to five buildings before the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) killed him.<ref name=\"CBC10\"/><ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=22 victims of N.S. rampage include retirees, pregnant health care worker, veteran|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt is the deadliest rampage in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob |publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The RCMP has yet to establish a motive.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n===April 18===\nBeginning at around 10:26 p.m., several residents of the rural beachside community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], called [[9-1-1]] to report gunshots and several fires.<ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=CBC News|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-new-details-timeline-nova-scotia-manhunt-1.5541561|title=RCMP give new details on timeline of manhunt for N.S. shooter|date=April 22, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020  |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead in Nova Scotia shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> According to ABC News, unnamed investigators say the incident may have begun as a case of [[domestic violence]] at a house where Wortman was trying to find a former partner.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"ABC2\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/death-toll-nova-scotia-shooting-rampage-increases-19/story?id=70251470|title=Nova Scotia shooting may have begun as a domestic violence dispute: Investigators|publisher=ABC News|last1=Deliso|first1=Meredith|last2=Pereira|first2=Ivan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA source told CNN Wortman burned down his own house before going to his former partner's residence, where he killed people living there and also nearby.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> When RCMP officers arrived on the scene twelve minutes later, at around 10:38 p.m., three houses on Portapique Beach Road and Orchard Beach Drive were found burning. Numerous victims were soon located, residents shot after fleeing the fires. One of the first officers to respond to the scene reported by radio that they could not locate an armed suspect, and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/nova-scotia-shooting-manhunt-details-1.5542025|title='They don't know if they've caught him': Recordings reveal chaos of Nova Scotia manhunt|publisher=CBC News|last=Gatehouse|first=Jonathon|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConfusion persisted for hours over whether a suspect had been apprehended.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> At 11:32 p.m., the RCMP posted a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the area to stay inside with their doors locked, and officers set up a search perimeter in the Portapique area. As the investigation developed overnight, they determined that the suspect had eluded them.<ref name=\":4\" /> By the morning of April 19, they said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=MassLive}}</ref>\n\n===April 19===\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported an explosion and gunfire at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. Another victim was then shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" />\n\nRCMP identified 51-year-old Gabriel Wortman as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and warned that he was impersonating a police officer by wearing an RCMP uniform and driving a replica police vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Between 10:04 and 11:04 a.m., he was seen in or near the communities of [[Glenholme, Nova Scotia|Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Onslow, Nova Scotia|Onslow]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating that he was travelling toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-timeline-of-nova-scotia-mass-shooting/|title=Timeline of Nova Scotia mass shooting|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=Globe and Mail}}</ref> A law enforcement source told CNN that during this time, Wortman began performing [[Traffic stop|traffic stops]] on random cars, and killing their occupants.<ref name=\"CNN\" /> At 10:54 a.m., surveillance video apparently captured Wortman pulling into a parking lot in [[Millbrook 27|Millbrook First Nation]] in the mock police vehicle, briefly getting out to put on a reflective vest, and then driving off.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Boynton|first=Sean|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6855907/nova-scotia-mass-shooting-new-video/|title=Video appears to show Nova Scotia shooting suspect stop, change clothes amid killing spree|date=April 22, 2020|work=Global News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt approximately 11:15 a.m., RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson encountered Wortman oncoming on [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2|Route 2]] in the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]], and rammed her cruiser into his replica to stop it.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/20/nova-scotia-shooting-details-emerge-in-gabriel-wortmans-rampage/|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Details emerge in suspect Gabriel Wortman's rampage|last=Sheehy|first=Kate|date=April 20, 2020|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|archive-date=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Witnesses reported that Wortman exited his vehicle and shot into Stevenson's; both cars caught fire, though accounts differ on when.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /> He then stole a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]] from a nearby motorist, and was next seen continuing south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] through [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]] at 11:24 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThirteen hours after police began pursuing him, at 11:26 a.m., Wortman was finally intercepted, shot, and killed by at least one officer at the [[Irving Oil#Big Stops|Irving Big Stop]] [[Rest area|service area]] in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> His death was confirmed by police at 11:40 a.m.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people, including Constable Heidi Stevenson. He shot another officer, who survived.<ref name=\"CBC10\" /><ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> One other person was injured.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> Victims were found in the communities of Portapique, Wentworth, Debert, Shubenacadie, Milford, and Enfield.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|title=Canada shooting: Death toll in Nova Scotia rises to 22|publisher=BBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422000411/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of Wortman's first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, his targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The dead are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" />\n\n==Perpetrator==\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as Gabriel Wortman, a 51-year-old [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer, his [[yearbook]] entry alluding to this.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020|last=Frisko|first=Bruce}}</ref> Acquaintances described him as a polite and house-proud man who often spent time at a seasonal home near [[Cobequid Bay]].<ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He did not have a firearms licence, and RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said the police will investigate how he obtained his weapons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/3a83av/nova-scotia-gunman-was-not-a-legal-firearms-owner-rcmp-says|title=Nova Scotia Gunman Was Not a Legal Firearms Owner, RCMP Says|publisher=Vice|last=Lamoureux|first=Mack|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman pleaded guilty to assault in 2002 and was sentenced to nine months of probation, in which he was prohibited from possessing weapons and ordered to undergo anger management counselling.<ref name=\"CTV6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rcmp-say-they-were-in-process-of-preparing-alert-when-gunman-was-killed-1.4906672|title=N.S. RCMP say they were 'in process' of preparing alert when gunman was killed|publisher=CTV News|last=Flanagan|first=Ryan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC8\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-criminal-record-1.5541176|title=Suspect in N.S. killings didn't have criminal record, but previously pleaded guilty to a crime|publisher=CBC News|last=Donkin|first=Karissa|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> He was also involved in two civil matters regarding property disputes, according to interviews and public records. A former acquaintance described how, in 2004, Wortman offered to help him when he had financial difficulties and was about to lose his house, only for Wortman to discreetly take ownership of the home away from him, evict him, and sell the property. In 2015, Wortman had been temporarily loaned a Portapique home a paternal uncle had purchased while he was in the process of selling his [[Edmonton]] condominium. Wortman refused to release the Portapique property back to him, claiming he was owed money, until the uncle eventually sold it.<ref name=\"CBC8\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6846920/nova-scotia-killer-financial-practices/|title='He stole my house': Nova Scotia killer had history of dubious financial practices|publisher=Global News|last1=Bell|first1=Stewart|last2=Russell|first2=Andrew|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement [[memorabilia]] and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his denture clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\" />\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with alcohol use and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFollowing the killings, the decorative signage on Wortman's denture clinic in Dartmouth, portraying a large smile and a set of dentures, garnered complaints from the public. In response, [[Halifax Regional Police]] removed the signage on April 22.<ref name=\"signage\">{{cite news |last1=April |first1=Allan |title=Police remove teeth, signage from denture clinic owned by N.S. shooter |url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/police-remove-teeth-signage-from-denture-clinic-owned-by-n-s-shooter-1.4907452 |publisher=CTV News |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Investigations==\n===Criminal===\nNo motive has been established for the killings, though they are not considered an act of [[terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, Chief Superintendent Leather said there were 16 crime scenes, including five structure fires, over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nOn the evening of April 21, the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] were dispatched to assist the RCMP in their investigation by providing them with additional personnel and supplies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/military-equipment-nova-scotia-rcmp-investigation-mass-killing-1.5540743|title=Military personnel, equipment to aid RCMP investigation into mass killing|publisher=CBC News|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLeather noted that Wortman's use of a police cruiser and wearing a police uniform allowed him to help evade detection for a long time. Owning police vehicles or uniforms is not a crime, but impersonating a police officer is.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Donkin |first1=Karissa |last2=Daigle |first2=Thomas |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-shooting-rcmp-vehicle-1.5539877 |title=Police uniform, mock RCMP cruiser key parts of investigation into N.S. shootings |work=[[CBC News]] |date=April 21, 2020 |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hill |first=Brian |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6851700/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-uniform-police-car |title=How a real uniform and replica police car helped the Nova Scotia gunman go undetected |work=[[Global News]] |date=April 22, 2020 |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNova Scotia's [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would conduct an investigation into the shooting of Wortman.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLeather said firearms used by the shooter were not legally licensed firearms and were illegally purchased, a transaction that will be investigated further.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kelownanow.com/news/news/National_News/Police_have_good_idea_guns_used_in_Nova_Scotia_mass_shooting_were_not_licensed/|title=Police have \u2018good idea\u2019 guns used in Nova Scotia mass shooting were not licensed|last=KelownaNow|website=KelownaNow|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n===Use of emergency alert===\nFollowing questions about why Nova Scotia did not use [[Alert Ready]], Canada's emergency population warning system, to warn the public about the killings and instead used popular [[social media]] platforms Twitter and [[Facebook]] to provide updates, RCMP officials said they had been dealing with an unfolding situation and details kept being updated many times. However, the areas affected had poor cellular Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not have used Twitter. Relatives of the victims pointed out that Alert Ready would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors, which could have saved lives.<ref name=\"CTV7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/u-s-citizens-in-nova-scotia-were-sent-additional-warning-during-deadly-rampage-1.4907139|title=U.S. citizens in Nova Scotia were sent additional warning during deadly rampage|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cooke|first=Alex|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-emergency-alert-1.5540220|title='I would not have let my wife leave': Widower blasts lack of emergency alert during N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/corrie-ellison-mass-shooting-brother-clinton-hiding-1.5541082|title=He was 'hunted' by the Portapique gunman and survived. His brother didn't|publisher=CBC News|last=Davie|first=Emma|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Chief Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process on alerting the public.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|last=Gorman|first=Michael|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC7\">{{cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/questions-remain-rcmp-ns-emergency-alert-1.5540100|title=Questions emerge about RCMP's failure to send emergency alert on gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, Leather said officers in Dartmouth were asked by the province about a warning at 10:15 am, but did not agree on details like wording before Wortman died 71 minutes later.<ref name=\"CTV6\" /> The [[List of diplomatic missions of the United States|United States Consulate]] in Halifax said it emailed American citizens in Nova Scotia warning them of the situation using the RCMP's information.<ref name=\"CTV7\"/>\n\n==Reactions==\nFlags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|work=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420223029/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing |publisher=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200421002715/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| archive-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]] expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening [[gun control]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He asked the media to not use Wortman's name or image: \"Do not give this person the gift of infamy.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|title=Canada's worst mass shooting leaves at least 18 dead|publisher=KKTV|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422085944/https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Elizabeth II]], [[monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], expressed her condolences, saying that she and [[Prince Philip]] were \"saddened by the appalling events\", and that her thoughts and prayers were with the people of Nova Scotia and all Canadians. She also paid tribute to the \"bravery and sacrifice\" of the RCMP and other emergency services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-crime-nova-scotia-britain/queen-elizabeth-sends-condolences-to-canada-after-nova-scotia-shooting-idUSKCN2231JF|title=Queen Elizabeth sends condolences to Canada after Nova Scotia shooting|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Reuters|last=Faulconbridge|first=Guy}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, the [[CN Tower]] was illuminated in blue and white, the colours of the [[Flag of Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia flag]], and also in RCMP red, blue, and gold in honour of Stevenson, on the quarter- and half-hours. On April 21, at [[Niagara Falls]], both the Canadian [[Horseshoe Falls]] and the [[American Falls]] were also illuminated in blue and white as a symbol of bi-national solidarity with Nova Scotia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/iconic-canadian-symbols-glow-blue-and-white-in-show-of-solidarity-with-nova-scotia-1.4907477|title=Iconic Canadian symbols glow blue and white in show of solidarity with Nova Scotia|publisher=CTV News|last1=Jerrett|first1=Andrea|last2=Price|first2=Melanie|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n* [[List of rampage killers in the Americas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/we-mourn-for-their-families-teacher-nurse-cancer-survivor-among-n-s-shooting-spree-victims-1.4903446 \"'We mourn for their families': Teacher, nurse, cancer survivor among N.S. shooting spree victims\"]. [[CTV News]]. April 20, 2020.\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "InedibleHulk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCriminal:Briefer.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "List of presidents of the United States by net worth", "text_new": "\n\n{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[Image:Donald_Trump_official_portrait.jpg|thumb|[[Donald Trump]], wealthiest U.S. president]]\n[[Image:Gwashington.jpeg|thumb|[[George Washington]], the first U.S. president and second-wealthiest president]]\n[[Image:Alincoln.jpeg|thumb|[[Abraham Lincoln]], one of the poorest presidents in terms of net worth.]]\n[[File:Harry S. Truman.jpg|alt=<nowiki>Truman had several failed business ventures and debts that took him very close to bankruptcy. He and his wife were also the first recipients of [[Medicare]] after it was signed into law.</nowiki>|thumb|[[Harry S. Truman]], the poorest U.S. President]]\n\t\nThe peak wealth of [[President of the United States|presidents of the United States]] has varied considerably. Debt and depreciation often meant that a president's net worth was less than $0 at the time of his death.<ref name=\"Wilson\">{{cite web|last1=Wilson|first1=Gaye|title=Monticello Was among the Prizes in a Lottery for a Ruined Jefferson\u2019s Relief|url=http://www.history.org/foundation/journal/winter10/jefferson.cfm|website=www.history.org|accessdate=April 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409111711/http://www.history.org/Foundation/journal/Winter10/jefferson.cfm|archive-date=April 9, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Most presidents before 1845 were extremely [[wealth]]y, including [[Andrew Jackson]] (who was born into [[poverty]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/topics/andrew-jackson|title=Andrew Jackson|work=HISTORY.com|accessdate=2015-09-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927091423/http://www.history.com/topics/andrew-jackson|archive-date=2013-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[George Washington]]. Many early presidents were [[Land tenure|landowners]], and some of them owned [[plantations in the American South|plantations]] and [[List of presidents of the United States who owned slaves|slaves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historical.ha.com/common/newsletter.php?inFrame=yes&id=3594&date=&type=histnews-tem120511|title=Heritage Auctions Newsletter: George Washington, Landowner|work=Historical.ha.com|accessdate=2015-09-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.nas.com/lopresti/ps.htm|accessdate=August 15, 2012|title=How many presidents owned slaves?|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120810184715/http://home.nas.com/lopresti/ps.htm |archivedate=August 10, 2012}}</ref> \t \n\t\nPresidents since 1929, when [[Herbert Hoover]] took office, have generally been wealthier than earlier presidents; with the exception of [[Harry S. Truman]], all presidents during this period were millionaires. These presidents have often received income from [[Autobiography|autobiographies]] and other writing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontheissues.org/Giving.htm |title=Giving, by Bill Clinton |publisher=Ontheissues.org |date= |accessdate=2015-09-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004044921/http://www.ontheissues.org/Giving.htm |archive-date=2015-10-04 |url-status=live }}</ref> Except for [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] and [[John F. Kennedy]], all presidents beginning with [[Calvin Coolidge]] [[List of autobiographies by presidents of the United States|have written autobiographies]]. In addition, many presidents--including [[Bill Clinton]]--have earned considerable income from public speaking after leaving office.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/05/us/politics/05clintons.html?pagewanted=all|title=Clintons Made $109 Million in Last 8 Years|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=McIntyre, Mike|date=5 April 2008|accessdate=15 August 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104131913/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/05/us/politics/05clintons.html?pagewanted=all|archive-date=4 November 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Tonner\">{{cite web|last1=Tonner|first1=Andrew|title=The 10 Richest U.S. Presidents --  The Motley Fool|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2016/11/20/the-10-richest-us-presidents.aspx|website=The Motley Fool|accessdate=April 16, 2017|language=en|date=Nov 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170313214222/https://www.fool.com/investing/2016/11/20/the-10-richest-us-presidents.aspx|archive-date=March 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n \nThe richest president in history is [[buttface]], who is the first billionaire president.<ref name=\"Seales\">Rebecca Seales, [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38637123 Eight ways President Donald Trump will make history] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612210526/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38637123 |date=2018-06-12 }}, BBC News (January 21, 2017).</ref><ref name=\"Gore\">Leada Gore, [http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/01/donald_trumps_net_worth_as_he.html Donald Trump's net worth as he takes office and Barack Obama's as he leaves] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109181256/http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/01/donald_trumps_net_worth_as_he.html |date=2018-01-09 }}, [[AL.com]] (January 19, 2017).</ref> His net worth, however, is not precisely known because [[the Trump Organization]] is privately held.<ref name=\"Seales\"/><ref name=\"Gore\"/> \n \n[[Harry S. Truman]] was the poorest U.S. president, with a net worth considerably less than $1 million. His financial situation contributed to the doubling of the presidential salary to $100,000 in 1949.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/savingandinvesting/the-8-poorest-us-presidents/ar-AAmSkeQ?fb_comment_id=1171497172969462_1171569652962214#page=9|title=The 8 poorest US presidents|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2019-05-03}}</ref> In addition, the [[Former Presidents Act#Pension|presidential pension]] was created in 1958 when Truman was experiencing financial trouble.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/01/20/news/obama-pension/index.html|title=Here's how much Obama's pension is worth|last=Isidore|first=Chris|date=2017-01-20|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2019-05-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503191536/https://money.cnn.com/2017/01/20/news/obama-pension/index.html|archive-date=2019-05-03|url-status=live}}</ref> Truman and his wife, Bess Truman, received the first [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] Cards in 1966 via the [[Social Security Amendments of 1965|Social Security Act of 1965]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medicareresources.org/basic-medicare-information/brief-history-of-medicare/|title=A brief history of Medicare in America|date=2019-05-01|website=medicareresources.org|language=en|access-date=2019-05-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502060707/https://www.medicareresources.org/basic-medicare-information/brief-history-of-medicare/|archive-date=2019-05-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==List of presidents by peak net worth==\n\nThe figures in the table below are all derived from 24/7 Wall St.'s 2016 valuation of each president's peak net worth. For purposes of 24/7 Wall St.'s valuation, a president's peak net worth may occur after that president has left office.<ref name=\"24/7 Wall St.\" /> To allow for a direct comparison, all of the figures have been adjusted for inflation to 2016 U.S. dollars.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"width:225px; height:14px;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:165px;\"| Net worth<br><small>(in mil. of 2016 US$)</small><ref name=\"24/7 Wall St.\">{{cite news|url=https://247wallst.com/special-report/2019/02/26/the-net-worth-of-the-american-presidents-washington-to-trump-2/|title=The Net Worth of the American Presidents: Washington to Trump|last=|first=|date=November 10, 2016|work=24/7 Wall St.|accessdate=April 10, 2019|publisher=247wallst.com|via=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410142809/https://247wallst.com/special-report/2019/02/26/the-net-worth-of-the-american-presidents-washington-to-trump-2/|archive-date=April 10, 2019|url-s