tle}}\n| official_languages                = {{hlist |[[Somali language|Somali]] <br />[[Arabic language|Arabic]]}}\n| demonym                = [[Demographics of Somalia|Somali]]\n| government_type                = [[Autonomy|Autonomous]] [[Presidential system|presidential democracy]]\n| leader_title1                = [[List of presidents of Galmudug|President]]\n| leader_name1                = [[Ahmed Abdi Kariye]]\n| leader_title2                = \n| leader_title3                = [[List of presidents of Galmudug|Vice President]]\n| leader_name3                = [[Ali Dahir (Ali Eid)]]\n| sovereignty_type                = [[Federation|Federal Member State]]\n| sovereignty_note                = within [[Somalia]]\n| established_event1                = Established\n| established_date1                = 14 August 2006<ref name=\"Gmifa\">{{cite news|title=Galmudug marks its fifth anniversary |url=http://www.sonna.net/content/galmudug-marks-its-fifth-anniversary |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130703092237/http://www.sonna.net/content/galmudug-marks-its-fifth-anniversary |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 July 2013 |accessdate=27 May 2019 |newspaper=SONNA |date=14 August 2011 }}</ref>\n| area_km2                = 78,279 <ref>name=\"ACFTAOASYDOAGM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mapdevelopers.com/area_finder.php?&points=%5B%5B5.426986467117847%2C45.4779052734375%5D%2C%5B5.038598014033392%2C45.773162841796875%5D%2C%5B5.000293327969875%2C46.04644775390625%5D%2C%5B4.392602231346782%2C46.198883056640625%5D%2C%5B4.395340740675732%2C46.35200500488281%5D%2C%5B4.003634793338907%2C46.417236328125%5D%2C%5B3.6309290128416167%2C47.0599365234375%5D%2C%5B3.6117413278386814%2C47.15675354003906%5D%2C%5B4.425463677921341%2C47.901763916015625%5D%2C%5B4.934622948213849%2C48.18328857421875%5D%2C%5B5.935339745680884%2C48.882293701171875%5D%2C%5B6.388636954544086%2C49.053955078125%5D%2C%5B6.383177873884563%2C48.492279052734375%5D%2C%5B6.486890400402608%2C47.99652099609375%5D%2C%5B6.934242777331261%2C46.9281005859375%5D%2C%5B6.803353105914645%2C46.8072509765625%5D%2C%5B6.596038418654293%2C46.6204833984375%5D%5D/|title= Map Developers|publisher=}}</ref>\n| area_rank                = \n| percent_water                = \n| population_estimate                = 2,500,000\n| population_census                = \n| population_estimate_year                = \n| population_estimate_rank                = \n| population_census_year                = \n| population_density_rank                = \n| GDP_PPP                = 250\n| GDP_PPP_year                = \n| GDP_PPP_rank                = 4444\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita                = 115\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita_rank                = 6rd\n| Gini                = <!--number only-->\n| Gini_year                = \n| Gini_change                = <!--increase/decrease/steady-->\n| Gini_ref                = \n| Gini_rank                = \n| HDI                = <!--number only-->\n| HDI_year                = \n| HDI_change                = <!--increase/decrease/steady-->\n| HDI_ref                = \n| HDI_rank                = \n| currency                = [[Somali shilling]]\n| currency_code                = SOS\n| time_zone                = [[East Africa Time|EAT]]\n| utc_offset                = +3\n| utc_offset_DST                = +3\n| time_zone_DST                = not observed\n| drives_on                = right\n| calling_code                = [[+252]] (Somalia)\n| cctld                = [[.so]]\n| official_website                = https://galmudug.gov.so\n| area_magnitude                = \n| areami\u00b2                = \n| population_density                = \n| population_densitymi\u00b2                = \n| iso3166code                = SO\n| today                = \n| image_flag2                = New_Flag_of_Galmudug_State_of_Somalia.svg\n}}\n'''Galmudug''' ([[Arabic]]: ''\u062c\u0644\u0645\u062f\u062c''), ({{lang-it|Galmudugh}}, officially '''Galmudug State''' ''(''[[Somali language|Somali]]'': Dowlad goboleedka Galmudug ee Soomaaliya)'' is a federal state in central [[Somalia]], with its capital at [[Dhusamareb]]. It is bordered to the north by the [[Puntland]] state, to the west by the [[Somali Region]] in Ethiopia, to the east by [[Somali Sea]] and to the south by [[Hirshabelle]] state. \n\nConsisting of the [[Galgaduud]] and [[Mudug]] regions, Galmudug's name is derived from a conflation of the names of the two regions.<ref>{{cite book | last=Hobbes |first=Cameron |date=2017 |title=Somalia and Democracy, a Task to Achieve |url=https://books.google.com/?id=BLYQDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT48&dq=galmudug#v=onepage&q=galmudug&f=false |location= |publisher= |page=48 |isbn=978-1542518512 |author-link= }}</ref><ref name=\"allafrica.com\">{{cite web|title=Somalia's Federal Govt Endorses Central State|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201407310912.html|website=All Africa|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gulf of Aden Security Review - February 12, 2016|url=http://www.criticalthreats.org/gulf-aden-security-review/gulf-aden-security-review-february-12-2016|website=The Critical Threats Project|accessdate=18 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202003614/http://www.criticalthreats.org/gulf-aden-security-review/gulf-aden-security-review-february-12-2016|archive-date=2 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>http://maritimelandsecurity.com/federalism-in-the-central-region/</ref><ref name=\"Introduction somalia\">{{cite web|title=Introduction somalia - |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/so.html |website=CIA Factbook}}</ref> Galmudug is a federal state within the larger [[Somalia|Federal Republic of Somalia]], as defined by the [[Constitution of Somalia|provisional constitution of Somalia]].<ref name=\"allafrica.com\"/>\n\n==Location==\nGalmudug is the most centrally located area in [[Somalia]]. It is situated about 750&nbsp;km from [[Mogadishu]], [[Bosaso]] and [[Harar]] in [[Ethiopia]]. The region is bordered to the east by the [[Somali Sea]], to the west by [[Ethiopia]], to the north by [[Puntland]], and to the south by the [[Hirshabelle State|Hirshabelle]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Establishment===\nOn August 14, 2006 the autonomous Galmudug region was established. [[Mohamed Warsame Ali]] 'Kiimiko' was elected as the new administration's President, and [[Galkayo]] was declared the new polity's capital.<ref name=\"Sgenlps\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Galmudug Elects New Leader, Pledges Security|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201208030100.html|accessdate=18 April 2013|newspaper=SMN|date=2 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe appellation ''Galmudug'' is a conflation of Galguduud and Mudug provinces.\n\nRelations between Galmudug and the Puntland region to its immediate north have historically been tense. However, the two regions gradually made strides toward strengthening inter-regional relations. To this end, representatives of the two autonomous administrations signed an accord in February 2011 in [[Garowe]], the capital of Puntland, wherein both governments officially agreed to cooperate on security, economic and social matters.<ref name=\"Aajsbpagg\">[http://www.somaliweyn.org/pages/news/Feb_11/PL-Galmudug-Accord.pdf An Agreement Jointly Signed by Puntland and Galmudug] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601002746/http://www.somaliweyn.org/pages/news/Feb_11/PL-Galmudug-Accord.pdf |date=2011-06-01 }}</ref>\n\n===Presidential elections===\nOn 1 August 2012, Galmudug's 25-seat parliament elected General Abdi Hasan Awale (Qaybdiid) as the region's new president. He replaced former president Mohamed Ahmed Aalin, who was receiving medical treatment abroad.<ref name=\"Sgenlps\"/> Qaybdiid had obtained 22 votes versus 1 vote for the other candidate, Abdisamad Nur Guled. Qaybdiid was subsequently sworn in as Galmudug President in a ceremony in Galkayo marking the 6th anniversary since the establishment of the Galmudug administration.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Qeybdid sworn in as Galmudug president| url=http://www.bar-kulan.com/2012/08/15/qeybdid-sworn-in-as-galmudug-president/ | work=Bar-kulan | date=2012-08-15 | accessdate=2012-08-16 }}</ref> During his inauguration speech, Qaybdiid reiterated his pre-election promises to firm up on regional security, expand his administration's control to areas that had not been covered by the regional authority, and foster relations with neighbouring regional states and national bodies.<ref>{{Cite web | first=Mohamed | last=Beerdhige | title=Galmudug Elects New President | url=http://www.somaliareport.com/index.php/post/3562 | work=Somalia Report | date=2012-08-01 | accessdate=2012-08-16 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804233213/http://www.somaliareport.com/index.php/post/3562 | archive-date=2012-08-04 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Official status===\nAs of 2013, Galmudug's official status as a federal state is in the process of being finalized. Qaybdiid's administration has asserted that Galmudug meets the requirements for official state status, as outlined in the federal constitution. {{As of|2013|4}}, the federal authorities have not accepted this claim.<ref name=Sgplcigs>{{cite news|title=Somalia govt 'pursuing leadership change in Galmudug': sources |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_govt_pursuing_leadership_change_in_Galmudug_sources_printer.shtml |accessdate=10 April 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=8 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925174303/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_govt_pursuing_leadership_change_in_Galmudug_sources_printer.shtml |archivedate=25 September 2013 }}</ref> Article 49 of the [[Constitution of Somalia|Provisional Federal Constitution]], which oversees the establishment of the Federal Republic of Somalia's constituent states, stipulates that \"based on a voluntary decision, two or more regions may merge to form a Federal Member State\".<ref name=\"Frspc\">{{cite web|title=The Federal Republic of Somalia - Provisional Constitution |url=http://www.somaliweyn.com/pages/news/Aug_12/Somalia_Constitution_English_FOR_WEB.pdf |accessdate=10 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130124010543/http://www.somaliweyn.com/pages/news/Aug_12/Somalia_Constitution_English_FOR_WEB.pdf |archivedate=24 January 2013 }}</ref> Since Galmudug only includes part of the official Mudug region, the federal Interior Minister Abdikarim Guled has urged the local Galmudug authorities to merge with other would be states, including [[Himan and Heeb]], to form one unitary state consisting of two or more regions, in accordance with the constitution.<ref name=Prsmoians>{{cite news|last=Somali Ministry of Interior and National Security|title=Press Release: Somali Ministry of Interior and National Security|url=http://www.radioogaal.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=651:somali-ministry-of-interior-and-national-security-&catid=38:news-in-english&Itemid=84|accessdate=10 April 2013|newspaper=Radio Gaal|date=26 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2014, the Federal Government of Somalia officially endorsed a new [[Central Regions State]], following a signed agreement in Mogadishu between representatives from Galmudug, Himan and Heeb, and [[Ahlu Sunna Waljama'a]]. The formalization ceremony for the new federal state was held at the [[Villa Somalia]] presidential compound and was presided over by President of Somalia [[Hassan Sheikh Mohamud]] and Prime Minister [[Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed]], with UN, EU, AU, IGAD and AMISOM envoys also in attendance. According to the Prime Minister's office, the Federal Government appointed a ministerial committee to guide the formation of the new state. It also organized a number of consultative meetings with the regional representatives, with each party eventually agreeing to establish a new administration in the Mudug and Galguduud regions. Additionally, the Central Regions State will be subject to the Provisional Federal Constitution.<ref name=\"Gsfgecsatd\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Federal Govt endorses central state after tripartite deal|url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Federal-Govt-endorses-central-state-after-tripartite-deal_printer.shtml|accessdate=31 July 2014|agency=Garowe Online|date=30 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812144757/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Federal-Govt-endorses-central-state-after-tripartite-deal_printer.shtml|archivedate=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Spmwatfnaics\">{{cite news|title=Somali Prime Minister welcomes agreement to form new administration in central Somalia|url=http://horseedmedia.net/news/2014/07/somali-prime-minister-welcomes-agreement-form-new-administration-central-somalia/|accessdate=31 July 2014|agency=Horseed Media|date=31 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812095626/http://horseedmedia.net/news/2014/07/somali-prime-minister-welcomes-agreement-form-new-administration-central-somalia/|archive-date=12 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2014, the autonomous Puntland regional administration in northeastern Somalia issued a statement rejecting the Central Regions State agreement on the grounds that it contravened certain clauses and articles in the [[Constitution of Somalia|Provisional Federal Constitution]] and breached Puntland's jurisdiction over the northern part of the Mudug province.<ref name=\"Gspwsffg\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Puntland withdraws support for Federal Govt|url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Puntland-withdraws-support-for-Federal-Govt_printer.shtml|accessdate=1 August 2014|agency=Garowe Online|date=1 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812144815/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Puntland-withdraws-support-for-Federal-Govt_printer.shtml|archivedate=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Spcitwfgfacs\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: Puntland cuts its ties with Federal Government following announcement of Central State|url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-puntland-cuts-its-ties-with-federal-government-following-announcement-of-central-state/|accessdate=1 August 2014|agency=Raxanreeb|date=1 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802165618/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-puntland-cuts-its-ties-with-federal-government-following-announcement-of-central-state/|archive-date=2 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Puntland Council of Ministers led by Puntland President [[Abdiweli Mohamed Ali]] further expressed dismay over sponsorship of and attendance during the agreement by representatives of the central government and the international community, respectively. It also suspended relations with the Mogadishu authorities, and recalled Puntland's representatives serving in the Federal Parliament, Federal Cabinet and Federal Constitutional Review Committee to the Puntland state capital of [[Garowe]] for consultations.<ref name=\"Gspwsffg\"/>\n\nOn 9 August 2014, the UN, EU and IGAD envoys for Somalia issued a joint statement assuring the Puntland administration that the new central state of Somalia would not include any territory under Puntland jurisdiction. According to the officials, federal government representatives and signatories had indicated prior to the signing of the central state agreement that the pact would only apply to Galguduud and Galmudug, while North Mudug would remain an integral part of Puntland state.<ref name=\"Sueaiefsscstwm\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: UN, EU and IGAD envoys for Somalia send concern letter to Puntland president after the region suspended ties with Mogadishu|url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-un-eu-and-igad-envoys-for-somalia-send-concern-letter-to-puntland-president-after-the-region-suspended-ties-with-mogadishu/|accessdate=21 August 2014|agency=Raxanreeb|date=17 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821040855/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-un-eu-and-igad-envoys-for-somalia-send-concern-letter-to-puntland-president-after-the-region-suspended-ties-with-mogadishu/|archive-date=21 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 24 August 2014, Federal Parliament Speaker [[Mohamed Osman Jawari]] announced that Federal MPs hailing from Puntland had begun brokering negotiations between the federal government and the Puntland regional administration.<ref name=\"Ssjhmembfap\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: Speaker Jawari hails MPs' efforts to mediate between FG and Puntland|url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-speaker-jawari-hails-mps-efforts-to-mediate-between-fg-and-puntland/|accessdate=24 August 2014|agency=Raxanreeb|date=24 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826160659/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-speaker-jawari-hails-mps-efforts-to-mediate-between-fg-and-puntland/|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 October 2014, a three-day conference in Garowe concluded with a 12-point agreement between the Federal Government and Puntland authorities, which stipulates that the earlier Central Regions State pact between the Galmudug and Himan and Heeb regional administrations only applies to the Galguduud and south Mudug provinces.<ref name=\"Spcdwfg\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Puntland clinches deal with Federal Govt|url=http://www.garoweonline.com/page/show/post/610/somalia-puntland-clinches-deal-with-federal-govt|accessdate=14 October 2014|agency=Garowe Online|date=14 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 December 2014, ahead of a state formation conference in Adado, the Federal Government appointed six committees to oversee the establishment of the prospective Central Somalia regional state. The steering bodies include a technical committee facilitating the creation of Central State, which is chaired by Halimo Ismail Ibrahim; a constitution committee, which is chaired by Abdinoor Moalim Mohamud; a reconciliation committee tasked with solving of differences and selection of delegates, which is chaired by Sheikh Omar Mohamud Mahad; a security, protocol and supervision committee, which is chaired by Uke Haji Abdirahman; a mobilization committee, which is chaired by Abdullahi Abdi Abdille; and a committee of accommodation of delegates and guests of honour, which is chaired by Dahir Hassan Guutaale.<ref name=\"Gfgfctffcs\">{{cite news|title=Federal government finalizes committees to facilitate formation of Central state|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=7641|accessdate=26 December 2014|newspaper=Goobjoog|date=25 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn late March 2015, President Mohamud and Dhusamareb traditional elders began talks over a possible relocation of the Adado conference to Dhusamareb. Mohamud preferred holding the summit in Adado, whereas the traditional elders favored Dhusamareb for security-related reasons and because the town had already recently hosted smaller reconciliation meetings.<ref name=\"Gdmcs\">{{cite news|title=Dhusa-Mareeb conference Spokesman: \"there is chance discuss about where hold state formation conference\"|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=12239|accessdate=27 March 2015|agency=Goobjoog|date=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, during consultative talks with local politicians and traditional elders, President Mohamud officially announced that Dhusamareb was slated to be the administrative capital of the Central State.<ref name=\"Gphaacuscs\">{{cite news|title=President Hassan Announces Administrative Capital of Upcoming Somali Central State|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=12690|accessdate=8 April 2015|agency=Goobjoog|date=8 April 2015}}</ref> On 16 April, President Mohamud officially launched the Central State formation conference in Adado. The summit was attended by Federal Cabinet ministers and MPs, state formation technical committee Chairperson Halima Ismael, UN Special Envoy to Somalia Ambassador Nicholas Kay, IGAD Special Ambassador Mohamed Abdi Afey, Ambassador of Turkey Olgen Bakar and Uganda Special Envoy Nathan Mugisha. According to Mohamud, traditional leaders are now tasked with selecting 510 delegates, who will then elect a new regional president within two weeks.<ref name=\"Ackoics\">{{cite news|title=Adado conference kicks off in central Somalia|url=http://www.garoweonline.com/page/show/post/2322/adado-conference-kicks-off-in-central-somalia|accessdate=16 April 2015|agency=Garowe Online|date=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nThe Galmudug area in central Somalia is predominantly inhabited by people from the [[Somali people|Somali]] ethnic group, with the larger [[Hawiye]] clan particularly the [[Hiraab]] sub-clan of the [[Hawiye]] well represented especially the [[Habar Gidir]] who makeup the majority of the populations in [[Galguduud]] and [[mudug|southern mudug]].<ref name=\"Ttare\">{{cite book|title=Transformation Towards a Regulated Economy|year=2000|publisher=WSP Transition Programme, Somali Programme|page=9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4eHqAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a sizable population of Marehan (Sade) [[Darod|Darood]] as well  primarily in the cities of [[Abudwak]] and [[Balanbale]].<ref>https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6ac0e37.html</ref> In addition, you will find members of the Murursade sub clan of [[Hawiye]] as well as Surre [[Dir (clan)|Dir]].\n\n==Administration== \nBy very contentious elections full of corruption, coercion manipulation and repression by the Federal Government of Somalia, [[Ahmed Abdi Kariye]] became the sixth president of Galmudug State in the year 2020. The [[List of Presidents of Galmudug|President of Galmudug]] is an executive head of state; the President functions as the head of state while the [[List of Chief Ministers of Galmudug|Chief Minister]] of Galmudug functions as the head of government. The President can appoint and dismiss Cabinet members but has to forward it to the chief minister. In August 2017, President Gelle named a new twenty-two members Cabinet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hornobserver.com/articles/535/Somalia-Galmudug-President-Unveils-New-Cabinet/|title=Somalia: Galmudug President Unveils New Cabinet|publisher=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hiiraan.com/news4/2017/May/141948/former_mp_elected_as_galmudug_president.aspx/|title=Former MP elected as Galmudug President|publisher=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/ahlu-sunnah-to-head-cabinet-in-brokered-deal-with-galmudug-state/|title=Ahlu Sunnah to head cabinet in brokered deal with Galmudug state|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe current [[List of Chief Ministers of Galmudug|chief minister]] of Galmudug is [[Mohamed Ali Hassan]] since 6 December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201801150245.html/|title=Somalia: Galmudug Chief Minister Wants Al- Shabaab Wiped Out Before 2022 Polls|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, the Galmudug administration appoints Governors for each of its constituent provinces. The Governor of the Mudug province is Awes Ali Said.<ref name=\"Ggaatofs\">{{cite news |title=Galmudug administration announce to open free schools |url=http://goobjoog.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1800:galmudug-administration-announce-to-open-free-schools&catid=128&Itemid=655 |accessdate=8 April 2014 |newspaper=Goobjoog |date=5 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408215031/http://goobjoog.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1800%3Agalmudug-administration-announce-to-open-free-schools&catid=128&Itemid=655 |archivedate=8 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, the Galmudug regional administration in conjunction with the federal Ministry of Interior and the U.S. Tess Agency laid down the foundation for a new government centre  in Gaalkacyo. The fourth such local project, the initiative follows the establishment of a new presidential office, social services center and football stadium.<ref name=\"Fslfglgc\">{{cite news|title=Foundation stone laid for Galkacyo Local Government Centre|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=6352|accessdate=19 November 2014|agency=Goobjoog|date=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, the Galmudug administration launched a campaign to dig sewages and drainages in the suburbs of [[Gaalkacyo]]. Galmudug municipal and police officials in the process also began clearing illicit structures and buildings to make way for the new collection and disposal systems.<ref name=\"Ggpbdis\">{{cite news|title=Galmudug Police Breaks Down Illegal Structures|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=12463|accessdate=2 April 2015|agency=Goobjoog|date=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Presidents===\nFor a comprehensive list of the presidents of Galmudug State, see the [[List of presidents of Galmudug]] article.\n\n==Education==\nEducational institutions in the Galmudug region are largely in the private sector.<ref name=\"Ggaatofs\"/> In March 2015, the Galmudug administration announced that it is slated to open free schools in the regional state. According to the Galmudug Minister for Education Mohamed Haashi Dhalo-Dhalo, the local government will finance the appointment of teachers to the new institutions. The federal Ministry of Education is also scheduled to launch a number of additional educational projects in the region.<ref name=\"Ggsdtofs\">{{cite news|title=Gal-Mudug State due to opens free school |url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=11855 |accessdate=16 March 2015 |agency=Goobjoog |date=16 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402134025/http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=11855 |archivedate=2 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nUniversities and colleges in Galmudug include SIMAD University in Adado, Central Regions University in Adado, Horn Africa University in Adado, Mudug University in Galkayo, Savannah University in Guriel.<ref name=\"Pimu\">{{cite web|title=Mudug University|url=http://www.placementindia.com/job-recruiters/company-mudug-university/|publisher=PlacementIndia|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> <ref name=\u201cSU\u201d>{{cite web|title=Savannah University|url= http://savannahuni.com/login/|publisher=SavannahUni|accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>Galgaduud university in Abudwak, Guriel and Dhusamareb.<ref>http://markacadeey.com/2017/06/somali-government-progress-activities-in-the-past-week-27-may-02-june-2017/</ref>\n\n==Galmudug Security Force==\n{{main|Military of Galmudug}}\n[[File:GalmudugSecurityForce.jpeg|thumb|A platoon in marching in [[Dhusamareb]].]]\nGalmudug Security Force (GSF) is the [[Armed Forces]] of the autonomous Galmudug region of Central Somalia.\n\nGalmudug Darawish Force are military units that operate under the sole authority of Galmudug state government. They are under the command of the Galmudug state President.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hornobserver.com/articles/238/Galmudug-Statement-on-the-American-Airstrike-against-its-armed-forces|title=Galmudug Statement on the American Airstrike against its armed forces|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://radioshabelle.com/galmudug-puntland-trade-blames-mudug-conflict/|title=Galmudug And Puntland States Trade Blames Over Mudug Conflict|publisher=}}</ref> Galmudug Darawish Force is the Main military force that is keeping Al-Shabab militants out of the region with the help of the state's intelligence units.\n\nGalmudug Police Force is a highly trained Police force which operates in Galmudug state, it is responsible for the security of the Autonomous region and the safety of the citizens of the Autonomous region.\n\nThe [[Galmudug Maritime Force]] is highly trained and highly equipped maritime force who safeguards the region's marine resources from piracy, illegal fishing, and other illegal activities of the coast of Somalia.<ref name=\"GFNP\">{{cite web|title=GFNP|url=http://www.marsecreview.com/2017/04/galmudug-forces-nab-pirates/|publisher=www.marsecreview.com|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nNational Intelligence and Security Agency (NISA) is Somalia's National Intelligence And Security Agency, it has a branch in Galmudug state where it works alongside the intelligence units of Galmudug security force. it helps federal states in Somalia neutralize terrorists and help prevent terrorist attacks nationwide through intelligence networks.<ref name=\"GANFFANVTEM\">{{Cite web|title=GANFFANVTEM|url=http://nepjournal.com/galmudug-and-nisa-forces-foil-attack-nab-vehicle-transporting-explosive-materials/|publisher=nepjournal.com|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nFor air transportation Galmudug is served by Oshaka Airport in [[Galkayo]], [[Dhusamareb Airport|Ugaas Noor airport]] in Dhusamareb, [[Adado|Adado International Airport]] (The Largest Airport), [[Guriel Airport]], and by the [[Obbia Airport]] (Hobyo Airport) in [[Hobyo]].<ref name=\"Wacoa\">{{cite web|title=Obbia Airport (CMO)|url=http://www.world-airport-codes.com/somalia/obbia-5389.html|publisher=World Airport Codes|accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> Additionally, [[Hobyo]] has a small but growing [[seaport]].<ref name=\"Icsti\">{{cite web|title=Istanbul conference on Somalia 21 \u2013 23 May 2010 - Draft discussion paper for Round Table \"Transport infrastructure\"|url=http://www.somalitalk.com/2010/may/istambul/transport.pdf|publisher=Government of Somalia|accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==State Flag==\n{{main|Flag of Galmudug}}\n[[File: Flag of Galmudug.svg|thumb|Galmudug [[Flag of Galmudug]].]]\n\nThe current flag of Galmudug was adopted on June 17, 2015, in Adado City. since 2006 Galmudug used the [[Flag of Somalia]] until 2010 when it adopted its first regional state flag.<ref>http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Somalia.html</ref>\n\nGalmudug's regional flag Design:\n\nWhite chevron bearing two green stars\n\nfacing horizontally on a light blue field\n\nbearing a white star on the right side.\n\n==Coat of arms==\n{{main|Coat of arms}}\n[[File: Galmudug State Logo.png|thumb|Galmudug [[Coat of arms]].|alt=|120x120px]]\n\nThe '''Coat of arms of Galmudug''' are nearly identical to the [[Somalia|Somali]] national [[coat of arms]], with the addition of a [[Dabqaad]] [[Somali]] incense burner a traditional handcraft made in [[El Buur]], and a silhouette of [[Vachellia tortilis]] tree to represent peace inside the shield. \n\n==Administrative divisions==\n                                                              [[File:Landscape_of_Guriceel.jpeg|thumb|[[Guriel]] District]]\n\n===Regions===\n{{Main|Regions of Somalia}}\nThe administrative divisions Galmudug State is divided into two regions which are [[Mudug]] and [[Galgaduud]].<ref name=\"allafrica.com\"/> These two regions are then divided into 10 districts.<ref name=\"Galgr\">{{cite web|title=Galgaduud Region|url=http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/121024_Administrative_Map_Galgaduud_A4.pdf|accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Mdgr\">{{cite web|title=Mudug Region|url=http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/121024_Administrative_Map_Mudug_A4.pdf|accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> However, according to [[CIA]] Factbook northern Mudug is part of [[Puntland]].<ref name=\"Introduction somalia\"/>\n\n{| align= border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin:0 0 0 1em; background:#fff; border:1px #aaa solid; border-collapse:collapse; text-align:left; font-size:95%;\n|- style=\"text-align:center; background: #efefef; border-bottom:2px solid black;\"\n! Region !! Capital !! Districts\n|-\n| [[Galgaduud]] || [[Dhuusamareeb]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5\n|-\n| [[Mudug]] || [[Galkayo]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5\n|-\n|}\n\n====Main cities====\n{{Largest cities of Galmudug|cities in Galmudug=}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|}}\n\n{{States of Somalia}}\n\n{{Somalia topics}}\n{{Countries of Africa}}\n{{Geography of Africa}}\n{{Africa topic |Climate of}}\n{{Countries and territories bordering the Indian Ocean}}\n\n[[Category:Galmudug| ]]\n[[Category:States of Somalia]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Geography of Somalia]]\n[[Category:Divided regions]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Autonomous region in somalia}}\n{{Infobox country\n| conventional_long_name                = Galmudug State\n| common_name                = Galmudug\n| native_name                = {{unbulleted list|item_style=font-size:88%; |{{native name|so|Dowlad goboleedka Galmudug ee Soomaaliya}} |{{native name|ar|{{lower|0.1em|{{resize|120%| \u0648\u0644\u0627\u064a\u0629 \u062c\u0644\u0645\u062f\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0635\u0648\u0645\u0627\u0644}}}}&nbsp;|italics=off}}|''{{transl|ar|Wilayat G\u0101lmu\u1e0dug a\u1e63-\u1e62\u016bm\u0101l}}''}}\n| image_flag                = \n| image_coat                = Galmudug State Logo.png\n| symbol_type                = Coat of arms\n| national_motto                = \n| national_anthem                = ''[[Qolobaa Calankeed]]''\n| image_map                = Galmudugmap2017.jpg\n| map_caption                = Territory of Galmudug<ref>{{Cite book |last=Mosley  |first=Jason |date=2017 |title=Somalia's Federal Future Layered Agendas, Risks and Opportunities|url=https://www.chathamhouse.org/sites/files/chathamhouse/field/field_document/20150902SomaliaFederalFutureMosley.pdf |location= |publisher=Chatham House |page=19 |isbn= |author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://somaliupdate.com/articles/10070/Federalism-in-Africa-The-Somalia-Case/|title=Federalism in Africa: The Somalia Case|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polgeonow.com/2017/08/somalia-war-who-controls-somalia-map.html?m=1/|title=Somalia Control Map & Timeline - August 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://icai.independent.gov.uk/html-report/uk-aid-conflict-affected-country-reducing-conflict-fragility-somalia/|title=UK aid in a conflict-affected country: Reducing conflict and fragility in Somalia|publisher=}}</ref>\n| capital                = [[Dusmareb]]\n| largest_city                = [[Dusmareb]]\n| coordinates                = {{coord|5|32|06|N|46|23|10|E|region:SO-GA|display=inline,title}}\n| official_languages                = {{hlist |[[Somali language|Somali]] <br />[[Arabic language|Arabic]]}}\n| demonym                = [[Demographics of Somalia|Somali]]\n| government_type                = [[Autonomy|Autonomous]] [[Presidential system|presidential democracy]]\n| leader_title1                = [[List of presidents of Galmudug|President]]\n| leader_name1                = [[Ahmed Abdi Kariye]]\n| leader_title2                = \n| leader_title3                = [[List of presidents of Galmudug|Vice President]]\n| leader_name3                = [[Ali Dahir (Ali Eid)]]\n| sovereignty_type                = [[Federation|Federal Member State]]\n| sovereignty_note                = within [[Somalia]]\n| established_event1                = Established\n| established_date1                = 14 August 2006<ref name=\"Gmifa\">{{cite news|title=Galmudug marks its fifth anniversary |url=http://www.sonna.net/content/galmudug-marks-its-fifth-anniversary |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130703092237/http://www.sonna.net/content/galmudug-marks-its-fifth-anniversary |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 July 2013 |accessdate=27 May 2019 |newspaper=SONNA |date=14 August 2011 }}</ref>\n| area_km2                = 78,279 <ref>name=\"ACFTAOASYDOAGM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mapdevelopers.com/area_finder.php?&points=%5B%5B5.426986467117847%2C45.4779052734375%5D%2C%5B5.038598014033392%2C45.773162841796875%5D%2C%5B5.000293327969875%2C46.04644775390625%5D%2C%5B4.392602231346782%2C46.198883056640625%5D%2C%5B4.395340740675732%2C46.35200500488281%5D%2C%5B4.003634793338907%2C46.417236328125%5D%2C%5B3.6309290128416167%2C47.0599365234375%5D%2C%5B3.6117413278386814%2C47.15675354003906%5D%2C%5B4.425463677921341%2C47.901763916015625%5D%2C%5B4.934622948213849%2C48.18328857421875%5D%2C%5B5.935339745680884%2C48.882293701171875%5D%2C%5B6.388636954544086%2C49.053955078125%5D%2C%5B6.383177873884563%2C48.492279052734375%5D%2C%5B6.486890400402608%2C47.99652099609375%5D%2C%5B6.934242777331261%2C46.9281005859375%5D%2C%5B6.803353105914645%2C46.8072509765625%5D%2C%5B6.596038418654293%2C46.6204833984375%5D%5D/|title= Map Developers|publisher=}}</ref>\n| area_rank                = \n| percent_water                = \n| population_estimate                = 2,500,000\n| population_census                = \n| population_estimate_year                = \n| population_estimate_rank                = \n| population_census_year                = \n| population_density_rank                = \n| GDP_PPP                = 250\n| GDP_PPP_year                = \n| GDP_PPP_rank                = 4444\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita                = 115\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita_rank                = 6rd\n| Gini                = <!--number only-->\n| Gini_year                = \n| Gini_change                = <!--increase/decrease/steady-->\n| Gini_ref                = \n| Gini_rank                = \n| HDI                = <!--number only-->\n| HDI_year                = \n| HDI_change                = <!--increase/decrease/steady-->\n| HDI_ref                = \n| HDI_rank                = \n| currency                = [[Somali shilling]]\n| currency_code                = SOS\n| time_zone                = [[East Africa Time|EAT]]\n| utc_offset                = +3\n| utc_offset_DST                = +3\n| time_zone_DST                = not observed\n| drives_on                = right\n| calling_code                = [[+252]] (Somalia)\n| cctld                = [[.so]]\n| official_website                = https://galmudug.gov.so\n| area_magnitude                = \n| areami\u00b2                = \n| population_density                = \n| population_densitymi\u00b2                = \n| iso3166code                = SO\n| today                = \n| image_flag2                = New_Flag_of_Galmudug_State_of_Somalia.svg\n}}\n'''Galmudug''' ([[Arabic]]: ''\u063a\u0627\u0645\u062f\u0648\u063a''), ({{lang-it|Galmudugh}}, officially '''Galmudug State''' ''(''[[Somali language|Somali]]'': Dowlad goboleedka Galmudug ee Soomaaliya)'' is a federal state in central [[Somalia]], with its capital at [[Dhusamareb]]. It is bordered to the north by the [[Puntland]] state, to the west by the [[Somali Region]] in Ethiopia, to the east by [[Somali Sea]] and to the south by [[Hirshabelle]] state. \n\nConsisting of the [[Galgaduud]] and [[Mudug]] regions, Galmudug's name is derived from a conflation of the names of the two regions.<ref>{{cite book | last=Hobbes |first=Cameron |date=2017 |title=Somalia and Democracy, a Task to Achieve |url=https://books.google.com/?id=BLYQDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT48&dq=galmudug#v=onepage&q=galmudug&f=false |location= |publisher= |page=48 |isbn=978-1542518512 |author-link= }}</ref><ref name=\"allafrica.com\">{{cite web|title=Somalia's Federal Govt Endorses Central State|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201407310912.html|website=All Africa|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gulf of Aden Security Review - February 12, 2016|url=http://www.criticalthreats.org/gulf-aden-security-review/gulf-aden-security-review-february-12-2016|website=The Critical Threats Project|accessdate=18 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202003614/http://www.criticalthreats.org/gulf-aden-security-review/gulf-aden-security-review-february-12-2016|archive-date=2 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>http://maritimelandsecurity.com/federalism-in-the-central-region/</ref><ref name=\"Introduction somalia\">{{cite web|title=Introduction somalia - |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/so.html |website=CIA Factbook}}</ref> Galmudug is a federal state within the larger [[Somalia|Federal Republic of Somalia]], as defined by the [[Constitution of Somalia|provisional constitution of Somalia]].<ref name=\"allafrica.com\"/>\n\n==Location==\nGalmudug is the most centrally located area in [[Somalia]]. It is situated about 750&nbsp;km from [[Mogadishu]], [[Bosaso]] and [[Harar]] in [[Ethiopia]]. The region is bordered to the east by the [[Somali Sea]], to the west by [[Ethiopia]], to the north by [[Puntland]], and to the south by the [[Hirshabelle State|Hirshabelle]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Establishment===\nOn August 14, 2006 the autonomous Galmudug region was established. [[Mohamed Warsame Ali]] 'Kiimiko' was elected as the new administration's President, and [[Galkayo]] was declared the new polity's capital.<ref name=\"Sgenlps\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Galmudug Elects New Leader, Pledges Security|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201208030100.html|accessdate=18 April 2013|newspaper=SMN|date=2 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe appellation ''Galmudug'' is a conflation of Galguduud and Mudug provinces.\n\nRelations between Galmudug and the Puntland region to its immediate north have historically been tense. However, the two regions gradually made strides toward strengthening inter-regional relations. To this end, representatives of the two autonomous administrations signed an accord in February 2011 in [[Garowe]], the capital of Puntland, wherein both governments officially agreed to cooperate on security, economic and social matters.<ref name=\"Aajsbpagg\">[http://www.somaliweyn.org/pages/news/Feb_11/PL-Galmudug-Accord.pdf An Agreement Jointly Signed by Puntland and Galmudug] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601002746/http://www.somaliweyn.org/pages/news/Feb_11/PL-Galmudug-Accord.pdf |date=2011-06-01 }}</ref>\n\n===Presidential elections===\nOn 1 August 2012, Galmudug's 25-seat parliament elected General Abdi Hasan Awale (Qaybdiid) as the region's new president. He replaced former president Mohamed Ahmed Aalin, who was receiving medical treatment abroad.<ref name=\"Sgenlps\"/> Qaybdiid had obtained 22 votes versus 1 vote for the other candidate, Abdisamad Nur Guled. Qaybdiid was subsequently sworn in as Galmudug President in a ceremony in Galkayo marking the 6th anniversary since the establishment of the Galmudug administration.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Qeybdid sworn in as Galmudug president| url=http://www.bar-kulan.com/2012/08/15/qeybdid-sworn-in-as-galmudug-president/ | work=Bar-kulan | date=2012-08-15 | accessdate=2012-08-16 }}</ref> During his inauguration speech, Qaybdiid reiterated his pre-election promises to firm up on regional security, expand his administration's control to areas that had not been covered by the regional authority, and foster relations with neighbouring regional states and national bodies.<ref>{{Cite web | first=Mohamed | last=Beerdhige | title=Galmudug Elects New President | url=http://www.somaliareport.com/index.php/post/3562 | work=Somalia Report | date=2012-08-01 | accessdate=2012-08-16 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804233213/http://www.somaliareport.com/index.php/post/3562 | archive-date=2012-08-04 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Official status===\nAs of 2013, Galmudug's official status as a federal state is in the process of being finalized. Qaybdiid's administration has asserted that Galmudug meets the requirements for official state status, as outlined in the federal constitution. {{As of|2013|4}}, the federal authorities have not accepted this claim.<ref name=Sgplcigs>{{cite news|title=Somalia govt 'pursuing leadership change in Galmudug': sources |url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_govt_pursuing_leadership_change_in_Galmudug_sources_printer.shtml |accessdate=10 April 2013 |newspaper=Garowe Online |date=8 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130925174303/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia_govt_pursuing_leadership_change_in_Galmudug_sources_printer.shtml |archivedate=25 September 2013 }}</ref> Article 49 of the [[Constitution of Somalia|Provisional Federal Constitution]], which oversees the establishment of the Federal Republic of Somalia's constituent states, stipulates that \"based on a voluntary decision, two or more regions may merge to form a Federal Member State\".<ref name=\"Frspc\">{{cite web|title=The Federal Republic of Somalia - Provisional Constitution |url=http://www.somaliweyn.com/pages/news/Aug_12/Somalia_Constitution_English_FOR_WEB.pdf |accessdate=10 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130124010543/http://www.somaliweyn.com/pages/news/Aug_12/Somalia_Constitution_English_FOR_WEB.pdf |archivedate=24 January 2013 }}</ref> Since Galmudug only includes part of the official Mudug region, the federal Interior Minister Abdikarim Guled has urged the local Galmudug authorities to merge with other would be states, including [[Himan and Heeb]], to form one unitary state consisting of two or more regions, in accordance with the constitution.<ref name=Prsmoians>{{cite news|last=Somali Ministry of Interior and National Security|title=Press Release: Somali Ministry of Interior and National Security|url=http://www.radioogaal.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=651:somali-ministry-of-interior-and-national-security-&catid=38:news-in-english&Itemid=84|accessdate=10 April 2013|newspaper=Radio Gaal|date=26 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2014, the Federal Government of Somalia officially endorsed a new [[Central Regions State]], following a signed agreement in Mogadishu between representatives from Galmudug, Himan and Heeb, and [[Ahlu Sunna Waljama'a]]. The formalization ceremony for the new federal state was held at the [[Villa Somalia]] presidential compound and was presided over by President of Somalia [[Hassan Sheikh Mohamud]] and Prime Minister [[Abdiweli Sheikh Ahmed]], with UN, EU, AU, IGAD and AMISOM envoys also in attendance. According to the Prime Minister's office, the Federal Government appointed a ministerial committee to guide the formation of the new state. It also organized a number of consultative meetings with the regional representatives, with each party eventually agreeing to establish a new administration in the Mudug and Galguduud regions. Additionally, the Central Regions State will be subject to the Provisional Federal Constitution.<ref name=\"Gsfgecsatd\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Federal Govt endorses central state after tripartite deal|url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Federal-Govt-endorses-central-state-after-tripartite-deal_printer.shtml|accessdate=31 July 2014|agency=Garowe Online|date=30 July 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812144757/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Federal-Govt-endorses-central-state-after-tripartite-deal_printer.shtml|archivedate=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Spmwatfnaics\">{{cite news|title=Somali Prime Minister welcomes agreement to form new administration in central Somalia|url=http://horseedmedia.net/news/2014/07/somali-prime-minister-welcomes-agreement-form-new-administration-central-somalia/|accessdate=31 July 2014|agency=Horseed Media|date=31 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812095626/http://horseedmedia.net/news/2014/07/somali-prime-minister-welcomes-agreement-form-new-administration-central-somalia/|archive-date=12 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2014, the autonomous Puntland regional administration in northeastern Somalia issued a statement rejecting the Central Regions State agreement on the grounds that it contravened certain clauses and articles in the [[Constitution of Somalia|Provisional Federal Constitution]] and breached Puntland's jurisdiction over the northern part of the Mudug province.<ref name=\"Gspwsffg\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Puntland withdraws support for Federal Govt|url=http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Puntland-withdraws-support-for-Federal-Govt_printer.shtml|accessdate=1 August 2014|agency=Garowe Online|date=1 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812144815/http://www.garoweonline.com/artman2/publish/Somalia_27/Somalia-Puntland-withdraws-support-for-Federal-Govt_printer.shtml|archivedate=12 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Spcitwfgfacs\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: Puntland cuts its ties with Federal Government following announcement of Central State|url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-puntland-cuts-its-ties-with-federal-government-following-announcement-of-central-state/|accessdate=1 August 2014|agency=Raxanreeb|date=1 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802165618/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-puntland-cuts-its-ties-with-federal-government-following-announcement-of-central-state/|archive-date=2 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Puntland Council of Ministers led by Puntland President [[Abdiweli Mohamed Ali]] further expressed dismay over sponsorship of and attendance during the agreement by representatives of the central government and the international community, respectively. It also suspended relations with the Mogadishu authorities, and recalled Puntland's representatives serving in the Federal Parliament, Federal Cabinet and Federal Constitutional Review Committee to the Puntland state capital of [[Garowe]] for consultations.<ref name=\"Gspwsffg\"/>\n\nOn 9 August 2014, the UN, EU and IGAD envoys for Somalia issued a joint statement assuring the Puntland administration that the new central state of Somalia would not include any territory under Puntland jurisdiction. According to the officials, federal government representatives and signatories had indicated prior to the signing of the central state agreement that the pact would only apply to Galguduud and Galmudug, while North Mudug would remain an integral part of Puntland state.<ref name=\"Sueaiefsscstwm\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: UN, EU and IGAD envoys for Somalia send concern letter to Puntland president after the region suspended ties with Mogadishu|url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-un-eu-and-igad-envoys-for-somalia-send-concern-letter-to-puntland-president-after-the-region-suspended-ties-with-mogadishu/|accessdate=21 August 2014|agency=Raxanreeb|date=17 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821040855/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-un-eu-and-igad-envoys-for-somalia-send-concern-letter-to-puntland-president-after-the-region-suspended-ties-with-mogadishu/|archive-date=21 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 24 August 2014, Federal Parliament Speaker [[Mohamed Osman Jawari]] announced that Federal MPs hailing from Puntland had begun brokering negotiations between the federal government and the Puntland regional administration.<ref name=\"Ssjhmembfap\">{{cite news|title=SOMALIA: Speaker Jawari hails MPs' efforts to mediate between FG and Puntland|url=http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-speaker-jawari-hails-mps-efforts-to-mediate-between-fg-and-puntland/|accessdate=24 August 2014|agency=Raxanreeb|date=24 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826160659/http://www.raxanreeb.com/2014/08/somalia-speaker-jawari-hails-mps-efforts-to-mediate-between-fg-and-puntland/|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 October 2014, a three-day conference in Garowe concluded with a 12-point agreement between the Federal Government and Puntland authorities, which stipulates that the earlier Central Regions State pact between the Galmudug and Himan and Heeb regional administrations only applies to the Galguduud and south Mudug provinces.<ref name=\"Spcdwfg\">{{cite news|title=Somalia: Puntland clinches deal with Federal Govt|url=http://www.garoweonline.com/page/show/post/610/somalia-puntland-clinches-deal-with-federal-govt|accessdate=14 October 2014|agency=Garowe Online|date=14 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 December 2014, ahead of a state formation conference in Adado, the Federal Government appointed six committees to oversee the establishment of the prospective Central Somalia regional state. The steering bodies include a technical committee facilitating the creation of Central State, which is chaired by Halimo Ismail Ibrahim; a constitution committee, which is chaired by Abdinoor Moalim Mohamud; a reconciliation committee tasked with solving of differences and selection of delegates, which is chaired by Sheikh Omar Mohamud Mahad; a security, protocol and supervision committee, which is chaired by Uke Haji Abdirahman; a mobilization committee, which is chaired by Abdullahi Abdi Abdille; and a committee of accommodation of delegates and guests of honour, which is chaired by Dahir Hassan Guutaale.<ref name=\"Gfgfctffcs\">{{cite news|title=Federal government finalizes committees to facilitate formation of Central state|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=7641|accessdate=26 December 2014|newspaper=Goobjoog|date=25 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn late March 2015, President Mohamud and Dhusamareb traditional elders began talks over a possible relocation of the Adado conference to Dhusamareb. Mohamud preferred holding the summit in Adado, whereas the traditional elders favored Dhusamareb for security-related reasons and because the town had already recently hosted smaller reconciliation meetings.<ref name=\"Gdmcs\">{{cite news|title=Dhusa-Mareeb conference Spokesman: \"there is chance discuss about where hold state formation conference\"|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=12239|accessdate=27 March 2015|agency=Goobjoog|date=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, during consultative talks with local politicians and traditional elders, President Mohamud officially announced that Dhusamareb was slated to be the administrative capital of the Central State.<ref name=\"Gphaacuscs\">{{cite news|title=President Hassan Announces Administrative Capital of Upcoming Somali Central State|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=12690|accessdate=8 April 2015|agency=Goobjoog|date=8 April 2015}}</ref> On 16 April, President Mohamud officially launched the Central State formation conference in Adado. The summit was attended by Federal Cabinet ministers and MPs, state formation technical committee Chairperson Halima Ismael, UN Special Envoy to Somalia Ambassador Nicholas Kay, IGAD Special Ambassador Mohamed Abdi Afey, Ambassador of Turkey Olgen Bakar and Uganda Special Envoy Nathan Mugisha. According to Mohamud, traditional leaders are now tasked with selecting 510 delegates, who will then elect a new regional president within two weeks.<ref name=\"Ackoics\">{{cite news|title=Adado conference kicks off in central Somalia|url=http://www.garoweonline.com/page/show/post/2322/adado-conference-kicks-off-in-central-somalia|accessdate=16 April 2015|agency=Garowe Online|date=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nThe Galmudug area in central Somalia is predominantly inhabited by people from the [[Somali people|Somali]] ethnic group, with the larger [[Hawiye]] clan particularly the [[Hiraab]] sub-clan of the [[Hawiye]] well represented especially the [[Habar Gidir]] who makeup the majority of the populations in [[Galguduud]] and [[mudug|southern mudug]].<ref name=\"Ttare\">{{cite book|title=Transformation Towards a Regulated Economy|year=2000|publisher=WSP Transition Programme, Somali Programme|page=9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4eHqAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a sizable population of Marehan (Sade) [[Darod|Darood]] as well  primarily in the cities of [[Abudwak]] and [[Balanbale]].<ref>https://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6ac0e37.html</ref> In addition, you will find members of the Murursade sub clan of [[Hawiye]] as well as Surre [[Dir (clan)|Dir]].\n\n==Administration== \nBy very contentious elections full of corruption, coercion manipulation and repression by the Federal Government of Somalia, [[Ahmed Abdi Kariye]] became the sixth president of Galmudug State in the year 2020. The [[List of Presidents of Galmudug|President of Galmudug]] is an executive head of state; the President functions as the head of state while the [[List of Chief Ministers of Galmudug|Chief Minister]] of Galmudug functions as the head of government. The President can appoint and dismiss Cabinet members but has to forward it to the chief minister. In August 2017, President Gelle named a new twenty-two members Cabinet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hornobserver.com/articles/535/Somalia-Galmudug-President-Unveils-New-Cabinet/|title=Somalia: Galmudug President Unveils New Cabinet|publisher=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hiiraan.com/news4/2017/May/141948/former_mp_elected_as_galmudug_president.aspx/|title=Former MP elected as Galmudug President|publisher=}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/ahlu-sunnah-to-head-cabinet-in-brokered-deal-with-galmudug-state/|title=Ahlu Sunnah to head cabinet in brokered deal with Galmudug state|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe current [[List of Chief Ministers of Galmudug|chief minister]] of Galmudug is [[Mohamed Ali Hassan]] since 6 December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201801150245.html/|title=Somalia: Galmudug Chief Minister Wants Al- Shabaab Wiped Out Before 2022 Polls|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, the Galmudug administration appoints Governors for each of its constituent provinces. The Governor of the Mudug province is Awes Ali Said.<ref name=\"Ggaatofs\">{{cite news |title=Galmudug administration announce to open free schools |url=http://goobjoog.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1800:galmudug-administration-announce-to-open-free-schools&catid=128&Itemid=655 |accessdate=8 April 2014 |newspaper=Goobjoog |date=5 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408215031/http://goobjoog.com/en/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1800%3Agalmudug-administration-announce-to-open-free-schools&catid=128&Itemid=655 |archivedate=8 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, the Galmudug regional administration in conjunction with the federal Ministry of Interior and the U.S. Tess Agency laid down the foundation for a new government centre  in Gaalkacyo. The fourth such local project, the initiative follows the establishment of a new presidential office, social services center and football stadium.<ref name=\"Fslfglgc\">{{cite news|title=Foundation stone laid for Galkacyo Local Government Centre|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=6352|accessdate=19 November 2014|agency=Goobjoog|date=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, the Galmudug administration launched a campaign to dig sewages and drainages in the suburbs of [[Gaalkacyo]]. Galmudug municipal and police officials in the process also began clearing illicit structures and buildings to make way for the new collection and disposal systems.<ref name=\"Ggpbdis\">{{cite news|title=Galmudug Police Breaks Down Illegal Structures|url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=12463|accessdate=2 April 2015|agency=Goobjoog|date=2 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Presidents===\nFor a comprehensive list of the presidents of Galmudug State, see the [[List of presidents of Galmudug]] article.\n\n==Education==\nEducational institutions in the Galmudug region are largely in the private sector.<ref name=\"Ggaatofs\"/> In March 2015, the Galmudug administration announced that it is slated to open free schools in the regional state. According to the Galmudug Minister for Education Mohamed Haashi Dhalo-Dhalo, the local government will finance the appointment of teachers to the new institutions. The federal Ministry of Education is also scheduled to launch a number of additional educational projects in the region.<ref name=\"Ggsdtofs\">{{cite news|title=Gal-Mudug State due to opens free school |url=http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=11855 |accessdate=16 March 2015 |agency=Goobjoog |date=16 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402134025/http://goobjoog.com/english/?p=11855 |archivedate=2 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nUniversities and colleges in Galmudug include SIMAD University in Adado, Central Regions University in Adado, Horn Africa University in Adado, Mudug University in Galkayo, Savannah University in Guriel.<ref name=\"Pimu\">{{cite web|title=Mudug University|url=http://www.placementindia.com/job-recruiters/company-mudug-university/|publisher=PlacementIndia|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> <ref name=\u201cSU\u201d>{{cite web|title=Savannah University|url= http://savannahuni.com/login/|publisher=SavannahUni|accessdate=6 February 2020}}</ref>Galgaduud university in Abudwak, Guriel and Dhusamareb.<ref>http://markacadeey.com/2017/06/somali-government-progress-activities-in-the-past-week-27-may-02-june-2017/</ref>\n\n==Galmudug Security Force==\n{{main|Military of Galmudug}}\n[[File:GalmudugSecurityForce.jpeg|thumb|A platoon in marching in [[Dhusamareb]].]]\nGalmudug Security Force (GSF) is the [[Armed Forces]] of the autonomous Galmudug region of Central Somalia.\n\nGalmudug Darawish Force are military units that operate under the sole authority of Galmudug state government. They are under the command of the Galmudug state President.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hornobserver.com/articles/238/Galmudug-Statement-on-the-American-Airstrike-against-its-armed-forces|title=Galmudug Statement on the American Airstrike against its armed forces|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://radioshabelle.com/galmudug-puntland-trade-blames-mudug-conflict/|title=Galmudug And Puntland States Trade Blames Over Mudug Conflict|publisher=}}</ref> Galmudug Darawish Force is the Main military force that is keeping Al-Shabab militants out of the region with the help of the state's intelligence units.\n\nGalmudug Police Force is a highly trained Police force which operates in Galmudug state, it is responsible for the security of the Autonomous region and the safety of the citizens of the Autonomous region.\n\nThe [[Galmudug Maritime Force]] is highly trained and highly equipped maritime force who safeguards the region's marine resources from piracy, illegal fishing, and other illegal activities of the coast of Somalia.<ref name=\"GFNP\">{{cite web|title=GFNP|url=http://www.marsecreview.com/2017/04/galmudug-forces-nab-pirates/|publisher=www.marsecreview.com|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nNational Intelligence and Security Agency (NISA) is Somalia's National Intelligence And Security Agency, it has a branch in Galmudug state where it works alongside the intelligence units of Galmudug security force. it helps federal states in Somalia neutralize terrorists and help prevent terrorist attacks nationwide through intelligence networks.<ref name=\"GANFFANVTEM\">{{Cite web|title=GANFFANVTEM|url=http://nepjournal.com/galmudug-and-nisa-forces-foil-attack-nab-vehicle-transporting-explosive-materials/|publisher=nepjournal.com|accessdate=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nFor air transportation Galmudug is served by Oshaka Airport in [[Galkayo]], [[Dhusamareb Airport|Ugaas Noor airport]] in Dhusamareb, [[Adado|Adado International Airport]] (The Largest Airport), [[Guriel Airport]], and by the [[Obbia Airport]] (Hobyo Airport) in [[Hobyo]].<ref name=\"Wacoa\">{{cite web|title=Obbia Airport (CMO)|url=http://www.world-airport-codes.com/somalia/obbia-5389.html|publisher=World Airport Codes|accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> Additionally, [[Hobyo]] has a small but growing [[seaport]].<ref name=\"Icsti\">{{cite web|title=Istanbul conference on Somalia 21 \u2013 23 May 2010 - Draft discussion paper for Round Table \"Transport infrastructure\"|url=http://www.somalitalk.com/2010/may/istambul/transport.pdf|publisher=Government of Somalia|accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==State Flag==\n{{main|Flag of Galmudug}}\n[[File: Flag of Galmudug.svg|thumb|Galmudug [[Flag of Galmudug]].]]\n\nThe current flag of Galmudug was adopted on June 17, 2015, in Adado City. since 2006 Galmudug used the [[Flag of Somalia]] until 2010 when it adopted its first regional state flag.<ref>http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Somalia.html</ref>\n\nGalmudug's regional flag Design:\n\nWhite chevron bearing two green stars\n\nfacing horizontally on a light blue field\n\nbearing a white star on the right side.\n\n==Coat of arms==\n{{main|Coat of arms}}\n[[File: Galmudug State Logo.png|thumb|Galmudug [[Coat of arms]].|alt=|120x120px]]\n\nThe '''Coat of arms of Galmudug''' are nearly identical to the [[Somalia|Somali]] national [[coat of arms]], with the addition of a [[Dabqaad]] [[Somali]] incense burner a traditional handcraft made in [[El Buur]], and a silhouette of [[Vachellia tortilis]] tree to represent peace inside the shield. \n\n==Administrative divisions==\n                                                              [[File:Landscape_of_Guriceel.jpeg|thumb|[[Guriel]] District]]\n\n===Regions===\n{{Main|Regions of Somalia}}\nThe administrative divisions Galmudug State is divided into two regions which are [[Mudug]] and [[Galgaduud]].<ref name=\"allafrica.com\"/> These two regions are then divided into 10 districts.<ref name=\"Galgr\">{{cite web|title=Galgaduud Region|url=http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/121024_Administrative_Map_Galgaduud_A4.pdf|accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Mdgr\">{{cite web|title=Mudug Region|url=http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/121024_Administrative_Map_Mudug_A4.pdf|accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> However, according to [[CIA]] Factbook northern Mudug is part of [[Puntland]].<ref name=\"Introduction somalia\"/>\n\n{| align= border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin:0 0 0 1em; background:#fff; border:1px #aaa solid; border-collapse:collapse; text-align:left; font-size:95%;\n|- style=\"text-align:center; background: #efefef; border-bottom:2px solid black;\"\n! Region !! Capital !! Districts\n|-\n| [[Galgaduud]] || [[Dhuusamareeb]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5\n|-\n| [[Mudug]] || [[Galkayo]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5\n|-\n|}\n\n====Main cities====\n{{Largest cities of Galmudug|cities in Galmudug=}}\n